40|$|A {{two-dimensional}} stochastic <b>point</b> <b>process</b> can {{be regarded}} as a random measure and thus represented as a (countable) sum of Delta Dirac measures concentrated at some points. Integration with respect to the <b>point</b> <b>process</b> itself leads to the concept of the continuous wavelet transform of a <b>point</b> <b>process.</b> Applying then suitable translation, rotation and dilation operations through a non unitary operator, we obtain a transformed <b>point</b> <b>process</b> which highlights main properties of the original <b>point</b> <b>process.</b> The choice of the mother wavelet is relevant and we thus conduct a detailed analysis proposing three two-dimensional mother wavelets. We use this approach to detect main directions present in the <b>point</b> <b>process,</b> and to test for anisotropy...|$|R
